The paper discusses secure multi-party computation (MPC) protocols, which are commonly studied in the cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-category. The focus of the paper is on reducing the number of communication rounds, which is a key aspect of distributed computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the use of new techniques for treating multi-fan-in gates, which is relevant to circuit complexity (cs.CC) and information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper proposes a less-than comparison protocol, which involves decision-making and optimization, and could be relevant to machine learning (cs.LG).
